Title : Creevykeel Court Tomb
Text : '''Creevykeel Court Tomb''' is one of the better examples of a court tomb in [[Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.megalithicireland.com/Creevykeel%20home.htm |title=Creevykeel home |publisher=Megalithicireland.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426234902/http://www.megalithicireland.com/Creevykeel%20home.htm |archive-date=2014-04-26 |dead-url=yes }}</ref> The monument is located on the foothills of [[Tievebaun Mountain]] close to the sea near [[Mullaghmore, County Sligo|Mullaghmore]] in [[County Sligo]].
[[File:Megawal16.png|thumb|Creevykeel]]

==History==
The building of the [[tomb]] dates back to the [[Neolithic Period]], 4000-2500 BC.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archaeology.ie/MonumentoftheMonth/CreevykeelCourtTombCoSligo/ |title=Creevykeel Court Tomb, Co. Sligo - National Monuments Service |publisher=Archaeology.ie |date= |accessdate=2014-04-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427011000/http://www.archaeology.ie/MonumentoftheMonth/CreevykeelCourtTombCoSligo/ |archivedate=2014-04-27 |df= }}</ref> The Creevykeel Court Tomb is made up of a long, trapezoid shaped cairn which encloses an oval court, and a burial chamber that is made up of two compartments at the north west of the court. In the back of cairn there are three subsidiary chambers which are built into the [[cairn]].

"The old name for Creevykeel is Caiseal a' Bhaoisgin, the Fort of Bhaoisgin, Bhaoisgin being the well near the cairn."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carrowkeel.com/sites/sligo/creeveykeel.html |title=Creevykeel Court Cairn &#124; Cliffoney, Co Sligo &#124; Caislean an Bhaoisgin &#124; Sacred Island Guided tours &#124; by Martin Byrne |publisher=Carrowkeel.com |date=1935-09-04 |accessdate=2014-04-26}}</ref>

==Archaeology==

===Excavations in 1935===
The Creevykeel Court Tomb was excavated in 1935 by the fourth Harvard archaeological mission, which was one part of scientific excavations that occurred in Ireland. The leader of the excavation was [[Hugh O'Neill (archaeologist)|Hugh O'Neill]].

